es a new introduction that puts Modern Architecture in its broader architectural, historical, and intellectual context for the first time. The subjects of these lively lectures--from "Machinery, Materials and Men" to "The Tyranny of the Skyscraper" and "The City"--move from a general statement of the conditions of modern culture to particular applications in the fields of architecture and urbanism at ever broadening scales. Wright's vision in Modern Architecture is ultimately to equate the truly modern with romanticism, imagination, beauty, and nature--all of which he connects with an underlying sense of American democratic freedom and individualism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aARCHITECTURE / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAcceleration.  aAd libitum.  aArchitectural Record.  aChrysanthemum.  aConstruction.  aCorniceconscious.  aDaily Princetonian.  aHolländische Architektur.  aHorizontal Gothic.  aModern Architecture.  aNew Republic.  aNew School.  aOrganic simplicity.  aRenaissance.  aThe Disappearing City.  aTradition.  aUsonians.  aWendingen.  aad nauseam.  aaluminum.  ablazing.  acardboard surface.  aceremonial.  acivilization.  acontain.  acreative sense.  ademonstrate.  adimensions.  aenfolding.  aextinguish.  afashion.  ahead-made.  aheartfelt.  ahypodermically.  aindividuality.  aintegral.  aintercommunication.  amasonry running.  amechanical.  amodernistic.  amunicipality.  aornamental.  apictorial.  aplastic.  apreliminary amble.  aquantitative.  areal shelter.  arubble-stone.  ascenepainting.  aubiquitous publicity.  aurbanisme.1 aLevine, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Neil.1 aSmith, E. Baldwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb4